
1---What is a Class?
A class is a blueprint or template used to create objects. It defines the attributes (data) and methods (behavior) of an object. It is a logical entity and does not occupy memory until an object is created.

What is an Object?
An object is an instance of a class. It represents a real-world entity, occupies memory, stores actual data, and is used to access the class's attributes and methods.

2--- Class vs Object
Class	        Object
Blueprint	Real thing      created from the blueprint
Logical entity	             Physical entity
Doesn't occupy memory by itself	  Occupies memory
Used to create objects	       Created from a class
One class can create many objects	   Each object has its own data


3----example
class Student {

    // Attributes (Instance Variables)
    int rollNo;
    String name;
    int age;

    // Method
    void study() {
        System.out.println(name + " is studying.");
    }

    // Method
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Student Details");
        System.out.println("Roll No : " + rollNo);
        System.out.println("Name    : " + name);
        System.out.println("Age     : " + age);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Creating Object
        Student s1 = new Student();

        // Assigning Values
        s1.rollNo = 101;
        s1.name = "Yash";
        s1.age = 22;

        // Calling Methods
        s1.display();
NOTE---A class is a logical blueprint, an object is a physical instance in memory, attributes describe the object's state, and methods define its behavior.
        s1.study();
    }
}
