1---Constructor
A constructor is a special member of a class that is automatically called when an object is created. Its main purpose is to initialize the object's data.

 Characteristics of a Constructor
1. Constructor name must be the same as the class name.
2 Constructor has no return type.
3 Constructor is called automatically.
4 Constructor executes only once per object.

Important Interview Questions
1. What is a constructor?

Answer:

A constructor is a special member of a class that is automatically called when an object is created to initialize the object's data.

2. Why do we use constructors?

To initialize object data automatically at the time of object creation.

3. Can a constructor return a value?

No. Constructors do not have a return type.

4. Can a constructor be private?

Yes. A private constructor is commonly used in the Singleton Design Pattern to prevent object creation from outside the class.

5. Can constructors be overloaded?

Yes. A class can have multiple constructors with different parameter lists.

6. Can constructors be inherited?

No. Constructors are not inherited by subclasses.

7. Can constructors be overridden?

No. Since constructors are not inherited, they cannot be overridden.

8. What happens if you don't write any constructor?

The Java compiler automatically provides a default constructor (only if you haven't written any constructor yourself).

9. What is constructor chaining?

Calling one constructor from another constructor in the same class using this(



