3-----Copy Constructor (C++ Only)

A copy constructor creates a new object as a copy of an existing object.

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student {

public:

    string name;

    Student(string n) {
        name = n;
    }

    Student(const Student &s) {
        name = s.name;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << name << endl;
    }
};

int main() {

    Student s1("Yash");

    Student s2 = s1;

    s2.display();

    return 0;
}

Output

Yash
Why?

Instead of writing values again, we copy another object's data.

Java does not have copy constructors built into the language. 
Objects are usually copied by creating a new object and copying fields manually or by using methods like clone().


