What are Access Modifiers?

Access modifiers control who can access variables, methods, and classes.

There are mainly three common access modifiers in both languages:

public
private
protected

Java also has one extra:
default (package-private)
1. public
Accessible from anywhere.

C++
class Student {
public:
    string name;
};
Student s;
s.name = "Yash";   // ✅
Java
class Student {
    public String name;
}
Student s = new Student();
s.name = "Yash";   // ✅

No difference.

2. private
Accessible only inside the same class.

C++
class Student {
private:
    int marks;
};
Student s;
s.marks = 90;   // ❌ Error
Java
class Student {
    private int marks;
}
Student s = new Student();
s.marks = 90;   // ❌ Error
Again, same behavior.

3. protected
Accessible:
Inside the class
By child classes

C++
class Person {
protected:
    int age;
};
class Student : public Person {

public:

    void show() {

        age = 21;   // ✅
    }
};
Java
class Person {

    protected int age;
}

class Student extends Person {

    void show() {

        age = 21;   // ✅
    }
}
Same behavior in inheritance.

4. Default (Only in Java)
This is the biggest difference.
If you don't write any access modifier:

class Student {
    int marks;
}
marks becomes package-private (default access).
It can be accessed only by classes in the same package.

C++ has no package system, so it has no equivalent modifier.

Biggest Difference: Default Access
C++
class Student {

    int age;
};

Is age default/package-private?

❌ No.

It is private by default because it's inside a class.

Java
class Student {

    int age;
}

age is not private.

It has default (package-private) access.

This is a very common interview question.
Interview Question
Q: What is the biggest difference between C++ and Java access modifiers?

Answer:

The biggest differences are:

Java has a default (package-private) access modifier, while C++ does not.
C++ supports friend functions and friend classes, but Java does not.
C++ supports public, protected, and private inheritance, whereas Java uses only extends, which behaves like public inheritance.


First Remember One Line ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
protected members can be accessed:

✅ Inside the same package.
✅ In subclasses, even if they are in a different package.
❌ Not by non-subclasses in a different package.

Most Asked Interview Question
Q:

Can a protected member be accessed in a different package?

Answer:

Yes, but only through inheritance. A subclass in a different package can access the inherited
protected member using this or super (or directly), but it cannot access it through a parent class object.


