1. Static Variable
What is a Static Variable?

A static variable is shared by all objects of a class.

There is only one copy of a static variable, no matter how many objects are created.

Why Do We Need a Static Variable?

Suppose every student belongs to the same college.

Without static

class Student {

    String name;
    int rollNo;
    String college = "Poornima";
}
Student s1 = new Student();
Student s2 = new Student();
Student s3 = new Student();

Memory

Student 1
---------
college = Poornima

Student 2
---------
college = Poornima

Student 3
---------
college = Poornima

Three copies of "Poornima" are created.

This wastes memory.

Solution
class Student {

    String name;
    int rollNo;

    static String college = "Poornima";
}

Memory

Method Area (Class Memory)

Student Class
--------------
college = Poornima

Heap

Student Object 1
name
rollNo

Student Object 2
name
rollNo

Student Object 3
name
rollNo

Now only one copy of college exists.

Every object shares it.

Example
class Student {

    String name;
    static String college = "Poornima";
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Student s1 = new Student();
        Student s2 = new Student();

        s1.name = "Yash";
        s2.name = "Rahul";

        System.out.println(s1.college);
        System.out.println(s2.college);
    }
}

Output

Poornima
Poornima
Changing Static Variable
class Student {

    static String college = "Poornima";
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Student s1 = new Student();
        Student s2 = new Student();

        s1.college = "JECRC";

        System.out.println(s1.college);
        System.out.println(s2.college);
    }
}

Output

JECRC
JECRC
Why?

Because there is only one shared copy of college.

Interview Definition

A static variable belongs to the class instead of individual objects. Only one copy is created and shared among all objects.

2. Static Method
What is a Static Method?

A static method belongs to the class, not to an object.

It can be called without creating an object.

Why Do We Need It?

Suppose you want to print the college name.

Without static

Student s = new Student();
s.displayCollege();

But the method only uses a static variable.

Creating an object is unnecessary.

Solution
class Student {

    static String college = "Poornima";

    static void displayCollege() {

        System.out.println(college);
    }
}

Call it directly:

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Student.displayCollege();
    }
}

Output

Poornima
Can Static Method Access Static Variable?
class Student {

    static String college = "Poornima";

    static void show() {

        System.out.println(college);
    }
}

✅ Yes

Can Static Method Access Instance Variable?
class Student {

    int age = 20;

    static void show() {

        System.out.println(age);
    }
}

❌ Compile Time Error

Why?

Because age belongs to an object, but a static method belongs to the class.

There may be many objects with different values of age.

Java doesn't know which object's age to use.

Correct Way
class Student {

    int age = 20;

    static void show() {

        Student s = new Student();

        System.out.println(s.age);
    }
}

Now the method has a specific object to access.

Why is main() Static?
public static void main(String[] args)

When the JVM starts your program, no object exists yet.

The JVM must call main() directly.

That's why main() is static.

Interview Definition

A static method belongs to the class and can be called without creating an object.

